textDisplay:
What I love about how Kuro writes character quests is the fact that some are either still connected to the rover trying to regain his/her lost memories despite the emphasis being in the other character or they add to the world-building.

This is apparent in Changli's quest but also in Yinlin's. While Jiyan and Lingyang adds to the world-building.

It's a good balance. I hope they continue with this writing and improve upon it. I was surprised to not have felt detached to the quest since I expected it to have nothing to do with the rover or the general narrative which is a huge blunder on some games like this.

Also, the music. Goddamn.

textDisplay: WuWa story is awesome. I had a great time already in 1.0. I didn't listen to this nonsense that it's bad and to skip. First scenes were bad, yeah, but then it was a very fun experience with exploring new world, with all those cutscenes and fights. 1.1 is a level higher, yeah. It has better build up and pace. But in the end both part of the stories are clearly in classic shounen style, focused on certain feelings, emotions. Don't fixate on details of the plot here, you will just miss the point, you might find some moments shallow or even cringy. Try to go with the flow and vibe with atmosphere and open up for feelings. Hope now people will stop underrating story and start paying more attention. Actually, although 'feelings' were in the focus for now, worldbuilding and hints about schemes, like those of Fractsidus, clearly have some more depth to them. I'm looking forward for more.

Okay, one thing to say. YangYang, my flippin' god, the first time I heard her in this quest it was so "UGHHHHH JUST END THIS ALREADY I'D RATHER ALREADY STOP PLAYING THIS" But I went through it. And this quest... piece of art Kuro, it's something you wanted to do in CBT1. Dark, and really intense, though I don't really like the entire "lore drop" that was so early implemented with the game of us being the creator of Jinzhou, and that was just dropped so... like the feeling without care, I don't know what it was when I heard that line from Ju√©, but it just felt really weird to drop something SO important so early into the games story, at least for me, dunno if it was for anyone else.
Also, I think we could've kept Phrolova's name a secret for a BIT longer instead of revealing it without proper introduction (and when we do get the official introduction with her and rover it will be just... kind of akward) or maybe it won't be and it will be executed next to flawlessly.
This story REALLY did a good job with animating expressions, I really like how lively everyone is in this story with the extra keyframes and just expressions as a whole. Facial animations don't lack either, and CUTSCENES. HOLY CRAP, CUTSCENES... they were just a work of art, like this one right here, how the fudge did you ACTUALLY do something no other gacha game has done till this time? MAKE A CUTSCENE LONGER THAN 2 MINUTES? THAT IS CRAZY. LIKE AN IN-GAME ONE. This cutscene in particular is so... how do I say it? It's ambient, you can feel the emotion and the stakes of overall everything Jinshi does, she feels like a human being that wants to do something for her people. To save them from damnation, and knows the consequences of what happens if she does fail. Rover doesn't really do anything in the fight just watches it from a far enough place. This was absolutely gorgeous, ALL Voice actors did good, maybe except Abby and ESPECIALLY YANGYANG. PLEASE, DO SOMETHING ABOUT YANGYANG, HER VOICE ACTOR FITS, BUT SHE IS JUST... Really sloppy and really all weird to me, I can't explain the feeling, it's just "weird".

Honestly, this story quest was really good
kuro cooked with this üî•üî•üî•

The 1.1 update was a HUGE step foward for Kuro Games. The EN voice acting was so much better, and the story was also improved. For me, the main improvement is the main character's weight on the story. In hoyoverse games, it is rare to see the main character interract vocally with others, this happened here for the entirety of the story. Huge props to Kuro Games for keeping the spirit of main character.
The new characters were immensely nice, the npc-s model worked fine, and the new enemy models are top notch as well.
The difficulty keep spiking up, wich should be the norm, and the exploration factor still has the grasp on the player, to urge them to keep playing.

Huge ups for Kuro games, however I would like to share an insight.
Spoiler alert:






When I first met Jinshi in the story, in the version 1.1, a "hoyoverse" moment happened.
She was supposed to be bleeding, according to Changli, hurt and tired. She was on the Mt. for a while and is currently were fighting 3 Glacio Dreadmanes, at the same time, who she managed to one-shot with ease. (Keep in mind that Glacio Dreadmanes are no joke in the game, they hit hard and have a lot of health.)
This happened when she was "supposed" to be hurt and tired. This feeling were thrown out of the window right there.

Her character model/skin was clean like snow. Nothing happened that would make the player worry for her, she didn't pant, she didn't look exhausted, she wasn't hurt.
I don't want to see her in blood, nor yelping out, no. I'm not saying that. I am saying that some little details should be added at times like theese. Dirt, dust!
This is what I would call a "hoyoverse" moment, where most of theese moments happen in the talk. Show, don't tell. You don't need to treasure girlies so much on screen, we are not snowflakes. The worry factor were thrown out of the window.

Remember 1.0? When the guy at the cannon died on screen infront of the main character? He was full of dirt and blood, and he told us that he bought enough time for the cannon, wich made the scene emotional. Being a random character instead a playeable one, this definetly was a HUGE step foward in gacha games history, in my opinion.

I am saying again, I didn't want to see Jinshi in blood. A little spec of dust on her cheeks, more of thoose "scales" should have been on her body, make her pant a little more, let the audience worry for her. (She is also pretty heavy waifu material, so showing her more vulnereable would fuel more emotion for the scene, in my opinion.)

Sorry for the wall of text, and well theese are just MY OPINION. It is totally possible that I am overreacting, I just see some hints that happened mostly in Genshin/hsr and it would ruin the immersion in my opinion. Mostly at least.
Overall the 1.1 update was a HUGE step foward, and I think It is one of the best updates, any gacha games had over the years.
Hats off Kuro Games, thanks for making theese improvements.
Also thanks for reading, cheers o/

textDisplay: Can I get an explanation of what the difference is?

@@thebest3702 Loong or Long refers to an eastern dragon (serpentlike body/often depicted as having divine powers to control water, lightning, and cause storms/often associated with large bodies of water like rivers and oceans). They use a different character when referring to western dragons (winged lizardlike creatures that often breath flame).
textDisplayAdj: thebest loong long refers eastern dragon serpentlike body often depicted divine power control water lightning cause storm often associated large body water like river ocean use different character referring western dragon winged lizardlike creature often breath flame

textDisplay:
@@thebest3702 OK, but I'm not an authority, you can take it into consideration.
The primary differences between "dragon" and "loong" are rooted in their cultural origins and symbolic meanings:
Dragon:
- Cultural Origin: Typically associated with European, Middle Eastern, and some Asian mythologies.
- Symbolism: Often symbolizes power, ferocity, and sometimes evil or chaos.
- Description: Generally depicted with wings, four legs, and the ability to breathe fire or venom.

Loong (or Long):
- Cultural Origin: Exclusive to Chinese mythology and culture.
- Symbolism: Represents prosperity, wisdom, and imperial authority, often associated with good fortune.
- Description: Typically portrayed as a wingless, serpentine creature with scales and may have features such as a mane, horns, and a pearl under its chin. Loongs are also known for having a more sinuous and elegant form compared to the more robust and aggressive European dragons.

I would feel differently if it was a much more emotional feeling cutscene, but it just...didnt feel that way. Maybe it was the tone of the voices, or the expressions, but i kinda felt like i just watched a scene that wouldnt have been any different if it had just been a scene in game where they stand around with dialogue boxes.

However, i will definitely say that the music has gotten a LOT better! The walk up the staircase and mountain fixed a lot of my concerns for the music; that was great!

textDisplay: They seem to be using 2 systems of romanization for mandarin, the Wade‚ÄìGiles way giving hsi and the (modern standard) Pinyin way giving Jue with the tonal mark. You are right hsi in Pinyin is xi, they probably choose hsi because foreigners don't know how to pronounce the sound denoted by x, trying to pronounce hsi would be closer than pronouncing x like in xerox that a lot of people do. Also these things are not words they are just pronunciation notations for single characters, they are meaningless by themselves, you need to know which characters they represent.

textDisplay:
You have two eyes, one head, two legs and two arms. You may have hair and eyes the same color as another person. In this case, you are also not unique, not interesting, and do not stand out from other people in any way. And if you look at it on a large scale, it's true. Everyone is the same, but we need to look deeper. So it is with games, books, movies and anything on this earth. If you judge everything so superficially, nothing is unique. Therefore there is no point in reading books of the same genre, trying games of the same genre or with the same mechanics etc.
Genshin is also not interesting in any way according to this logic, because it's just a mixture of different projects. Nevertheless, there is something special about it, the developers were able to create a product that stands out and is liked by many.
Why should WW be worse? As I understand it, this is a herd instinct, because now it is fashionable to be a skeptic who calls everything a clone. It is sad.

textDisplay:
Dear Kuro Games Team,

I hope this email finds you well. I am a big Fan of your game, "Wuthering Waves." We have thoroughly Loved the immersive experience your team has created, and it has become one of our Most anticipated games.

We are writing to you today with a suggestion that We believe could enhance the game's accessibility and attract a broader audience. We have noticed that the game currently does not support the Arabic language, and We wanted to inquire about the possibility of adding Arabic language to Wuthering waves

Arabic is spoken by millions of people around the world, and by incorporating Arabic into the game, you have the opportunity to reach a significant player base who may currently feel excluded due to the language barrier. Adding Arabic language support can contribute to a more inclusive gaming environment, allowing players from Arabic-speaking regions to fully enjoy and understand the intricacies of the game.

Furthermore, offering the game in Arabic can open up new markets and potentially increase the game's popularity. Many gamers in the Middle East and North Africa region, where Arabic is predominantly spoken, are eager to engage with high-quality games that resonate with their culture and language.
Thank you for reading

textDisplay:
The entire game revolves around sound and waves. As Jinyan said in the first open beta. "We do not fear ring of the bell, but the silence that follows."

And for Science (The Fermi Paradox), the "silence" he's referring to is the "Great Silence", an extinction event where a powerful extradimensional race exterminates a lesser race that is still incapable of interstellar travel or even communication, hereby "silencing" it's voice, before it can be heard in the universe. Where a race might get a chance to survive.

It's a fight. A fight to ensure our voice will be heard loud and clear across the universe, that we refused to be silenced.

Everything in the game is music/waveform themed. Characters are called "Resonators" (devices that amplify sounds/waves by reflecting them), and their finishers "Resonance" (the activity of amplifying sounds/waves), and their combos: "Concerto"(musical composition of different instruments, or in Wuthering Waves' case: different characters) a captured enemy is appropriately called an "Echo", because it's literally what is left of them (The lingering sound that gets reflected back).
